description.text:
It was my son's idea to create a dinosaur skull that would sing jingle bells. This is the result of that project. The bottom jaw is controlled via a servo mounted in the base. In this video you can see the skull in action singing jingle bells.
http://youtu.be/Z-ojvIRqI_Q Undubbed with circuit board visible
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0hoYsfMroyg

I assembled the skull by brushing the surface with acetone, and then connecting the pieces together and securing it with rubber bands.  I dissolved scrap abs plastic pieces in a jar with acetone overnight.  I then added glow in the dark pigment to the abs and acetone mixture.  I really like the texture that this gives when dry, its a very bone-like texture.  After the skull is finished how you wish carefully cut the bottom jaw from the upper piece.  I finished the bottom box by brushing with acetone the sanding smooth.  I used oil paints to try and give it a wood look.  I used acetone as the medium for the oil paints.  This worked quite well and I will be exploring using oil paints on abs more in the future.  I gave it a few coats of spray lacquer to make it shiny.  The bottom jaw connector is printed in two pieces join the two pieces by brushing with acetone. Connect wire to jaw pivot(see photo). Connect the stand skull mount to the bottom of the upper skull.  It is helpful to brush the surface well with acetone letting it get nice and gooey.  It should fit nice and flush with the obtrusion in the back of the upper skull.  Connect the bottom pivot stand piece to the top.  Connect the bottom jaw pivot to the lower jaw.  Assemble rest of the stand.  The bottom stand part pushes through the bottom of the box.  Install servo motor in the bottom of the box.  Cut wire to length and connect to servo.

remixed_from.title: Bearing blocks for standard 8mm linear bearings (Wanhao duplicator i3).

description.text:
Bearing Blocks are used by most 3D Printers to allow for movement along one or more axis in combination with Linear Bearings.

This particular combination bypasses the need for the use of Ball Bearings. This allows for the same basic movements to be performed with a lesser of degree of noise and wear to the smooth rods. Lubrication is also no longer needed.

The bearings used in V1 are Igus Part# RJ4JP-01-08 as obtained from them and should fit over an 8mm smooth rod. The bearing blocks are made for the Wanhao Duplicator i3.

Keep in Mind that I have not used these blocks to print yet BUT, have placed them over an 8mm rod and they are very smooth. I also spent some time ensuring that printing is made easier and that there are no gaps in the blocks.

◘ALTHOUGH THIS COMBINATION IS MY CREATION AS A WHOLE, ITS BASIC BUILDING BLOCKS WERE MADE BY OTHERS AND CREDIT SHOULD GO TO "tahustvedt" FOR THE BEARING BLOCKS AND "Igus-USA" FOR THE BEARINGS THEMSELVES. ☺

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2+

Infill:

15-100%

Notes:

◘For the Wanhao Duplicator i3, Print 2 Cut & 1 Uncut for the X Axis Carriage.

◘I highly recommend using Igus Filament to print these bearings as that is what they recommend, however, it is very very very expensive. And so, you should try PETG or ABS first. I used only 15% infill and the part is very strong, but you can always go higher. Resolution shouldn't Matter.

◘Keep in mind that there will be some shrinkage in the material as it cools. If this happens, you have 2 options: Ask and provide exact changes that you would like and I'll resize it accordingly, OR, use a file or drill to make the opening larger. Also keep in mind that they will eventually conform to the rods and become smoother as you use them.

◘DO NOT USE PLA as it will deform under the heat generated by the movement.

Found this model hiding around in an old hard drive, along with a couple of other models I had worked with many years ago. Since I could not find a model for the Highwind on Thingiverse, I decided to share this one, as the Highwind is probably one of my favorite ships in the Final Fantasy series.

Uploaded is the original model updated to a new format, as the original was in a format of a now defunct 3d modeling software. I have also provided the cuts that I made for my initial print of this model. Feel free to cut it up to whatever works for you. I will most likely be updating this model to make it easier to assemble once printed, as when I printed this originally I just sliced to what I thought would be easier to print and glued the parts together. Small details like the antenna and wires were not added on like the original model. For those I would probably use some extracted filament to make the wire and a small bit of filament for the antenna (though that is just my way of tackling it). Also I am aware that there are some irregularities in the model when it comes to symmetry, this will be fixed.

Pictured print was printed on a Monoprice Maker Select and printed on ABS. Had some issues with the quality on original print mainly due to poor setup, as some parts were printed prior to adding crucial modifications to the printer.

Enjoy and make sure to post your results if you print it!

title: Parametric stand for my parametric bottle tray

description.text: This is a stand which allows my parametric bottle trays to be stacked, although I guess it could have other uses. It should work OK with the customiser. The variables to input are the inside width, the inside length, the inside height and how thick you'd like the walls to be. As well as that, you need to decide where you would like the opening. The choices are "0" which would make a cage. That would make it difficult to get at whatever is underneath but I've left the option in. The other choices are "1" which leaves an opening along the length (x axis), "2" which leaves an opening along one side (y axis), 3 which leaves openings along both sides (makes a "U" shape) and "4" which leaves openings at both ends. Basically, measure the tray (or other object) that this is to go over, and add a couple of mm for clearance and use these as the inside dimensions and then decide where you want the opening to be.

This thing is a functional object and doesn't need to be pretty. I suggest using the fastest speed and biggest layer height you can get away with to speed up the print time.

The open scad file creates a base which is a "cube" with the length of the sides being the inside dimensions plus the wall thickness. This forms the top but of course it needs to be printed upside down. Then sides are added depending on which option was chosen for an opening. To speed up printing and save filament, holes are added because it doesn't need to be solid. The number of holes and their position is calculated from the overall dimensions.

description.text:
This is the next step in my attempt to make a Sarrus linkage based 3D printer.  The idea is to have a cartesian mechanism without those long rods and bearings.
I built three of the Mark III and mounted them in a x-y arrangement as shown.  They can move over a square about 105 mm wide, and someday may carry an extruder.  They are driven by DC motors taken from inkjet printers.  These motors are driven in a servo arrangement using quadrature optical encoders and optical strips removed from the same printers.

Print:
2 end pieces
2 armatures
3 spine pieces
6 hinge plate type a
6 hinge plate type b
1 motor plate (modify to fit your motor)
1 belt plate
1 pulley plate
1 opto plate
1 DB9 bracket Do a lot more stuff (details available upon request) like trimming, drilling out holes, etc.
Mount either a stepper motor with belt (not shown) Make three of these things and connect them as shown.

description.text:
I wanted some good base level illumination on my Delta 3D printer. LED strips are so much better than LED diodes, so I made a simple little slide in case for a small 3528 LED strip. The LED strips are only 2 sections long (6 LEDs) with 2 wires soldered to the bottom end of the strip (which is hidden under the little cover at the end). The hole in the bottom end is angled to make it easier to feed the wires through. You can attach them to the frame with small cable ties or some good quality double sided carpet tape.

If 3 strips are too bright for you, (e.g. if you want to film what you are printing) you can either disconnect 1 (or 2 or 3) or you can put a potentiometer on the power line to control the brightness.
There are no specific print settings for these, default printer setup should be fine.

Love hurts and I love the new UM2+ feeder. But I decided that my poor finger shall not pain no more and quickly designed this little wedge. It is to be inserted below the lever that releases the pressure on the filament. Print with two shells and 100% infill (very quick print).

Btw. please note the expertly designed hole on the bottom where a small, round 3x3mm neodym magnet can be inserted so the wedge snaps to metallic parts on the printer. The magnet should go all the way in but I printed the wedge with 3 shells and the hole is too tight... oh well. :)

comments.text:
Shells are also called "walls". This is the outer perimeter of the object and it is dictated by the nozzle width. If you print with a 0.4mm nozzle, two shells means 20.4mm = 0.8mm. The more shells you have, the stronger the object will be (this depends on infill too but from my experience less infill and more shells is better than more infill and less shells).
However recent slicers do perform some tricks where they "lie" about the nozzle width and you'd end up with 3 shells equaling 1.5mm instead of 30.4mm = 1.2mm...

I'm going to make a version without the tabs as well, but that might take a few days since I'm a total noob at 3D drawing and it takes a while to get it the way I want :) UPDATE 12-29-2013 V1.0 of my KK2 casing is now available.. Added the requested slot for the voltage cable.
Reduced the size of the screw holes in the top of the casing and fixed a few other minor details I've discovered since printing V0.6 With the case "upgraded" to V1 this is no longer a "work in progress" and there will most likely not be any more changes to it. No, there is no V0.7 - 0.9 :) Enjoy, and happy flying.. UPDATE 09-14-2013 V0.6 of my KK2 casing is now available.. I made some small adjustments to the buttons to accommodate the fact that the buttons on the KK2 aren't always perfectly aligned. I've made the holes 0.5mm wider, 0.4mm deeper and slightly tapered and now they should work with any KK2 board straight off the printer, at least they do that with my two KK2 boards.. I've added symbols above the buttons on the front just for cosmetic reasons :) And as promised, there is now a version without the mounting tabs. All the parts are available as individual STL's or as a tray with and without the mounting tabs. I made a mess when filling the symbols with white paint so it doesn't look as good as it should, I will make another one and take a new picture later on, but for now the one I've got will have to do :)

Not much to say really.. Print it and drop your KK2 board in the case and close it up :)  
The buttons and front may require some trimming depending on how hard you squish the first layer.  
If you print one, please submit a "I made one" here on Thingiverse so I can see how it turned out.  
Thank you..

comments.text: This printed very nicely on the 3D systems Ekocycle but when we tightened down the screws, the piece stated to split in half down the middle splitting the layers. Splitting could possibly be prevented by printing in the vertical instead of horizontal.  We will have to try.  What are your experiences?
comments.author: CLPorter01

comments.text: Motor mounts are a tricky make in my experience. This was one of my first models, i've since tried with varying success other techniques and designs. Yes, printing vertically is better to prevent layer splitting, but at a certain point with this design in PLA or ABS you will split at the screw entry when you buckle it down. Also, printing vertical makes the actual print harder, especially depending on your printer and slicer. I haven't posted them yet, but i'm moving to a 2 part design with a heaver duty top section to prevent material splitting. The two part design makes printing much easier. If you want a quick fix, i suggest taking the design file and beefing up the thickness of the top part of the 'clamp'. Make a flat spot there, and use a washer. Distribution of the force over the area will help to reduce the splitting. At some point though, material will either give on the clamp section or the thread in on the PLA/ABS. I'll try to post a new design soon, with FTC season going i've been doing a lot of designing. Happy building!
